post_text:
The Agua Fria Union High School District is a 1:1 technology district and will loan a device to students. Students are expected to have the school device daily; personal devices can not be used during the school day for class work. Please review the information located in the Student Rights & Responsibilities Handbook, regarding the 1:1 technology program.

Parents/Guardians have the opportunity to purchase a protection plan through the district for $30 per school year per device. Payment for the Device Protection Plan must be made by Friday, September 11 to be active for the 2020-2021 school year.

FOOD SERVICE DURING REMOTE LEARNING:

AFUHSD will be providing meal service via bus routes to our students during their remote learning instruction.

Each day students will receive one breakfast meal and one lunch meal. The cost of the meal will depend on the student's meal status. If you would like to participate in our meal service via bus routes, please complete this form.

We encourage all families to apply for Agua Fria Union High School District Free or Reduced Lunch program. In addition to receiving free or reduced-price lunch, it has many other cost benefits when it comes to athletic and academic programs.

To access an online application visit our website or use the following link: https://family.titank12.com/application/new?identifier=3ZRQJ3

SUMMER OFFICE HOURS AND VISITOR POLICY:

The AFUHSD is committed to the safety of our staff, students, families, and guests we serve. Although buildings will be open with a reduced staff, we are requesting that all business occur electronically, virtually, or through phone communication.

Summer office hours will be in effect from Monday, June 1 to Thursday, July 16. Office hours will be Mondays through Thursdays with the exception of July 2; offices will be closed in observance of Independence Day.

Please call for assistance or to set up an appointment:
District Office (623) 932-7000

Visitor policy can be accessed here:

2020-2021 SCHOOL YEAR ONLINE REGISTRATION OPTION AVAILABLE JULY 6th üìÖ

If you are a new parent/guardian enrolling a student new to our district, please click the link and follow the steps to create a ParentVUE account, which will then allow you to register your student for the current 2020-21 school year: https://afsd.edupoint.com/login_parent_oen.aspx

If you're a parent/guardian with an existing ParentVUE account and want to enroll a student new to our district for the 2020-21 school year, please use the same link and login to your ParentVUE account.

If your student previously attended a school in this district, you will not be able to register your student using Online Registration. You can download a registration packet from our website, fill it out, and take it to your boundary school.

post_text: Our food service workers are always appreciated in normal times, but these are not normal time and now more than ever we have a whole new level of gratitude for our essential staff. During this crisis, not only are they preparing meals, but they are also helping to distribute them, too‚Äîwearing masks to work, boarding school buses to distribute meals grab-and-go meals at community locations, braving the heat, and directly interacting with families. By performing these essential services, our food service workers are often putting their own health, and that of their families, at risk. Some many of our families rely on meals from schools as their primary source of food, so this work cannot stop. A big thank you goes out to all our essential workers, including food service workers, buses drivers and warehouse staff that help prepare and deliver food to our community!
text: Our food service workers are always appreciated in normal times, but these are not normal time and now more than ever we have a whole new level of gratitude for our essential staff. During this crisis, not only are they preparing meals, but they are also helping to distribute them, too‚Äîwearing masks to work, boarding school buses to distribute meals grab-and-go meals at community locations, braving the heat, and directly interacting with families. By performing these essential services, our food service workers are often putting their own health, and that of their families, at risk. Some many of our families rely on meals from schools as their primary source of food, so this work cannot stop. A big thank you goes out to all our essential workers, including food service workers, buses drivers and warehouse staff that help prepare and deliver food to our community!

post_text:
AFUHSD is partnering with Avondale & Litchfield Elementary School Districts to ensure children have access to healthy meals during Arizona‚Äôs school closure. Student safety & wellness are of the utmost priority & the tri-district collaboration protects children from food insecurity.

Both elementary districts are offering Grab & Go meals to any child age 18 & under, no matter where they live. With two nutritious meals in one convenient location, all children can have a healthy breakfast & a healthy lunch each weekday while schools are closed due to COVID-19. Children must be present at time of pick up. The meals are offered at no cost to families. This program is 100% funded by the USDA.

The Governing Board voted and approved the closing of all District schools beginning March 16th through March 27th in an effort to prevent the community spread of COVID-19, and to protect the safety of students, staff, and the community.

Teachers, administrators, and District staff have been working diligently to prepare a plan for our students to participate in online learning beginning Wednesday, March 18. This plan will be finalized on Monday and teachers will receive training on Tuesday. This plan will be communicated in detail to students and families on Tuesday, March 17th.

post_text:
Career and technical education, or CTE, is education that directly prepares students for high-wage, high-demand careers. CTE covers many different fields, including health care, information technology, advanced manufacturing, hospitality and management and many more. CTE encompasses many different types of education, from classroom learning to certification programs to work-based learning opportunities outside the classroom.

Over 90% of graduates who earn 2-3 CTE credits enroll in college. Students with greater exposure to CTE are more likely to graduate, enroll in college, be employed and earn higher wages.

February is CTE Month so let's celebrate the value of CTE and the achievements and accomplishments of CTE programs.

Kiwanis of Litchfield attended the Agua Fria High School District governing board meeting to present funding for the Millennium High School Band program. Thank you Agua Fria District for allowing Kiwanis to support the Fine Arts in the West Valley. Kiwanis also expressed their appreciation to the Agua Fria InterKey Club and Millennium Key Club for their members who volunteer early every Saturday morning providing critical community service to local families in need.

post_text:
A bond provides the district additional funding to use for capital items, such as new buildings, additions or
renovations to buildings, school buses, equipment and technology. The funding requested by the 2019 election
will address school safety and fund critical repairs. The District has school buildings that are now over 60 years old and in desperate need of renovation. Other areas in need of
renovation include restroom facilities, air conditioning and HVAC systems, and other major systems that have outlived their useful lives. These areas will be renovated with modern efficient systems.
Learn more about how the 2019 bond would impact our AFUHSD schools: https://www.aguafria.org/cms/lib/AZ01902191/Centricity/ModuleInstance/14/Bond%20Fact%20Sheet.pd

post_text: Wow, great job #CanyonViewHighSchool horse judging team!üê¥
shared_text:
Canyon View High School
March 11, 2019 at 11:34 AM ¬∑

Our horse judging team- Micheala Cartrette, Elizabeth Harcharik, Carly Messer and Peyton Stone- went to state at the University of Arizona for their first state competition as a chapter! The horse judging contest consists of a 50 question test from a test bank of 500 questions; then they are presented 4 classes of different horses that they must evaluate composition and use on (given only about 10 minutes per class), rank each class of 4 horses, and then they must present 2 sets of oral reasons defending their ranking of horses to a set of judges.

Out of the 40 teams, our team of ALL freshmen, competing against juniors and seniors, placed 13th overall! Great job, ladies!

post_text: It's that time again...tax season is upon us. But on the bright side, it's the perfect opportunity to make a contribution to your school! You can receive a State Income Tax credit for up to $200, or $400 for joint filings. Arizona Revised Statute, ARS 43-1089.01, gives you this opportunity to help your local school, so why not take advantage & help out your school. That's what we call a win-win! Visit our website to learn more: https://www.aguafria.org/site/Default.aspx?PageID=5515
